<header class="header">
  <h1>Best Netting for Carrot Rust Fly vs Cabbage Moth</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    These two pests require different levels of protection — and the wrong netting won’t stop either one effectively.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    <strong>For most gardeners, fine insect mesh is required for carrot rust fly, while standard insect netting is usually enough for cabbage moth.</strong>
  </p>
  <p>
    Not all garden netting is the same. The size of the openings determines which pests it can actually block, and carrot rust fly and cabbage moth are very different in size and behavior.
  </p>
  <p>
    Choosing the wrong netting can leave crops exposed even if they appear covered.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Quick Answer: What Works Best?</h2>

  <div class="quickAnswerBox">
    <ul class="plainList">
      <li><strong>Carrot rust fly:</strong> ultra-fine insect mesh.</li>
      <li><strong>Cabbage moth:</strong> standard insect netting.</li>
      <li><strong>Best overall:</strong> fine mesh if you want protection from both.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p>
    Smaller pests require tighter mesh — and that changes everything about how the system performs.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Mesh Size Matters</h2>

  <p>
    The effectiveness of netting comes down to the size of the openings. Larger mesh allows airflow and light but may let small insects pass through.
  </p>

  <p>
    Finer mesh blocks smaller pests but can reduce airflow and increase heat buildup under the cover.
  </p>

  <p>
    Choosing the right balance depends on which pest you are trying to stop.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Carrot Rust Fly: What You Need</h2>

  <p>
    Carrot rust flies are small and can pass through many standard netting materials. To stop them effectively, you need a finer mesh that creates a true barrier.
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>requires tight mesh spacing</li>
    <li>must be sealed well at the edges</li>
    <li>works best with low tunnel or hoop setups</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Gaps at the edges often cause more problems than the mesh itself.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Cabbage Moth: What You Need</h2>

  <p>
    Cabbage moths are larger and easier to block with standard insect netting.
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>does not require ultra-fine mesh</li>
    <li>benefits from good airflow</li>
    <li>works well with lighter netting materials</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    For brassicas, airflow and ease of use often matter more than maximum mesh density.
  </p>
</section>

