<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Tradeoffs of Fine Mesh</h2>

  <p>
    While fine mesh provides better pest protection, it also reduces airflow and can increase temperature under the cover.
  </p>

  <p>
    This can affect plant growth, especially in warmer conditions or during summer.
  </p>

  <p>
    Managing ventilation becomes more important with tighter mesh.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Get Wrong</h2>

  <h3>Using Mesh That Is Too Large</h3>
  <p>
    This is the most common mistake when trying to control carrot rust fly.
  </p>

  <h3>Not Sealing the Edges</h3>
  <p>
    Even perfect mesh will fail if insects can enter from underneath.
  </p>

  <h3>Overheating the Crop</h3>
  <p>
    Fine mesh needs airflow management to avoid heat buildup.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How to Set Up Netting Properly</h2>

  <ol class="plainList">
    <li>Use hoops or supports to keep netting off the plants.</li>
    <li>Secure edges tightly to the soil or bed frame.</li>
    <li>Check regularly for gaps or lifting.</li>
    <li>Adjust ventilation if using fine mesh.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    A well-installed system matters as much as the material itself.
  </p>
</section>

